🆕 __Build Challenge__

🎵 We're starting out 2020 with some great tunes (not tuna 🎣 ) and we want you to help make an amazing music box with your favorite song in it!  Use those note blocks, build an amazing structure, and help us jam out while getting your favorite song stuck in everyone else’s head! 🎵 

:snow_golem:  **Music Box - January 24 to February 7**

📄 __Guidelines:__
:earth: Must be built in Minecraft Earth
:loading: This should be a brand new build and not be something that you've already built
:grass_block:  Build plate size will not matter & won't be a factor in judging
:mining: Feel free to ask for advice pertaining to your build in #music-box-challenge 
:mob_of_me: All work must be done by one individual
:fast_parrot: Remember, this is for fun only
📌If it's a submission picture, please feel free to ask a moderator to pin it.
:sign: __Winning submissions may be used in social media__ :friends:

Final submission for the #music-box-challenge...

For my build, I've gone for a simple, classic music box. Mainly because I kinda ran out of time just getting the music done, so it was gonna have to be basic.

Along with the nice dark timber frame and golden hinges and clasps, it has what every traditional music box should have - a pretty ballerina with a tutu and tiara.

This was the smoothest recording I could manage - somehow, despite having no moving parts, block updates, or talent, the pretty ballerina with the tulip in her hair (fur? slime? scales?) still managed to increase lag. A lot.

I couldn’t come up with a way to end the loops so I used TNT to halt them, because explosions are fun 🙂   The build is a nightclub in an old warehouse. Unfortunately both the bartender and DJ wanted to wander out of their areas so I had to lower their floors a bit to keep them safe. The DJ’s name is a reference to Carrier Current, which is a method of transmitting radio signals along rail lines.*
